article.description: The Liberty survived a  sensational performance by Tina Thompson to defeat the Comets and post their first victory.
article.headline: Thompson scores career-high 35 in loss
article.linkText: Thompson's 35 can't stop Comets fizzle in NY
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Becky Hammon is adjusting well to her new
leadership role with the New York Liberty.

Hammon scored 10 of her 22 points in the final six minutes and
the Liberty won their home opener, 68-62 against the Houston Comets
on Sunday.

"I helped our team down the stretch," Hammon said. "It was me
tonight but it will be someone else another night. The point guard
position takes a natural leadership role, so being a leader is
something that I have to do every day."

Hammon switched to the point this season in place of 
Teresa Weatherspoon, who signed with the Los Angeles Sparks in the
offseason after seven years in New York.

"Things have changed around here, not for the better and not
for the worse," Hammon said. "Things are just different, and as
long as we play together we will win."

Tina Thompson had a career-high 35 points and eight rebounds,
setting a WNBA single-game record by scoring 56.5 percent of her
team's points.

Thompson topped Katie Smith, who scored 56.3 percent of her
team's points for Minnesota when she had 40 against Detroit in
2001.

Sheryl Swoopes added 15 points for the Comets. Houston has lost
six straight regular season games at Madison Square Garden since a
79-54 victory on July 8, 1998.

Elena Baranova had 12 points and 14 rebounds, and Vickie Johnson
added 11 points and six assists for the Liberty.

After Thompson hit two free throws to tie the score for the last
time at 54 with 7:45 remaining, Hammon gave New York the lead for
good two minutes later with a three-point play.

New York shot 43 percent from the field (25-for-58) -- including
5-for-13 on 3-pointers -- while limiting Houston to 34 percent
shooting (22-for-64).

"We broke down on our individual defense," Comets coach Van
Chancellor said. "They did a great job."

Chancellor was unhappy with the play of his backcourt.

"I just cannot get the ball where I want it and when I want
it," he said. "Give (the Liberty) credit, but I got guards ...
we've been working on this since April 26, they have no earthly
idea what their coach wants them to do. On offense nor on defense.

"It's going to get better. We're going to practice enough,
we're going to get better."

The Liberty led 30-27 at halftime and stretched the lead to six
on Crystal Robinson's 3-pointer in the opening minute of the second
half.

Thompson, whose previous career high was 31 points at Portland
on June 23, 2002, pulled Houston within 57-56 with two free throws
with 5½ minutes to go.

"Tina had a great game, but fortunately we were able to stop
the rest of the team," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said.

Hammon then took over for the Liberty, driving through the lane
and hitting shots and drawing fouls down the stretch. She hit a
jumper and then converted a three-point play to give the Liberty a
62-56 lead with 3:14 left.

"I liked how she pushed the ball," Adubato said. "I thought
she did a very good job. Her decision making was good and her
clutch shooting was great."

The Comets got within two points again on a pair of free throws
by Thompson with 2:19 remaining, but New York scored the game's
final six points.

Houston started the game off strong, taking an 8-0 lead two
minutes in. However, New York scored 20 of the next 26 points,
including a 13-2 run during a six-minute stretch that turned a 12-7
deficit to a 20-14 lead with 6:37 remaining in the half.

The Liberty took their biggest lead of the game at 26-16 nearly
three minutes later, before the Comets closed the half with an 11-4
run.
